  "summary": "Josephine returns home with Madge, sporting a head bandage. Despite Madge's suggestion to rest, Josephine insists on going to the pond to see her fish. The narrator follows her and discusses the recent developments, including the discovery of a will leaving all of the grandfather's assets to Sophia. Josephine admits she knew this because she had been eavesdropping. She also reveals she knew Brenda and Lawrence were involved in something suspicious because she observed Lawrence hiding things in the water closet, noting that he was not a person who typically performed plumbing repairs.\n\nEdith de Harvilland summons Josephine and later speaks with the narrator. Appearing exhausted and dejected, Edith expresses a desire for Brenda to receive a fair legal defense, despite her previous dislike for her. She feels a sense of responsibility regarding Brenda's future but remains indifferent toward Lawrence. The narrator informs Edith of his plan to drive to London, and she asks to accompany him, requesting to be dropped off at Debenham Street and later Harley Street to avoid traveling with Margaret and Sophia.\n\nSeeking further information, the narrator meets with Inspector Taverner. Taverner explains that while the case against Brenda and Lawrence is strong, the evidence is largely circumstantial. He notes that the incriminating love letters found behind the sink imply a conspiracy to be together after the husband's death, but a defense lawyer could argue the letters refer to the husband's expected natural death. Taverner concludes that the outcome depends on whether the jury finds the pair sympathetic or views them as a typical criminal duo.",
